    <section>
        <h1>The Problem: Emotional Trading</h1>

        <h2>2.1 Cognitive Biases in Trading</h2>
        <p>
            Behavioral finance research has identified numerous cognitive biases that affect trading performance:
        </p>

        <h3>Availability Heuristic</h3>
        <p>
            Traders overweight recent or memorable events when assessing probabilities. For example, after witnessing a sharp crash, traders may overestimate the likelihood of further declines, even when statistical data suggests otherwise.
        </p>

        <h3>Anchoring Bias</h3>
        <p>
            Initial reference points (such as purchase price) disproportionately influence subsequent decisions. Traders often hold losing positions simply because selling would "realize" a loss relative to their anchored entry price.
        </p>

        <h3>Herd Behavior</h3>
        <p>
            Social proof and FOMO drive traders to follow crowd sentiment rather than conducting independent analysis. This leads to buying tops and selling bottoms in cyclical fashion.
        </p>

        <h2>2.2 Information Overload</h2>
        <p>
            Modern traders have access to more data than ever before, but this abundance creates paralysis and confusion. Key challenges include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Conflicting signals across different timeframes and indicators</li>
            <li>Noise vs. signal differentiation in social media and news</li>
            <li>Inability to process on-chain data effectively without technical expertise</li>
            <li>Difficulty integrating micro (short-term) and macro (long-term) perspectives</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>2.3 The Need for Rational Analysis Tools</h2>
        <p>
            What traders need is not more information, but better synthesis and interpretation of existing data. This is where artificial intelligence excels: processing vast datasets, identifying statistical patterns, and presenting actionable insights free from emotional contamination.
        </p>
    </section>

