            Aigen AI employs a diverse set of ML techniques optimized for different aspects of market analysis:
        </p>

        <h3>Supervised Learning Models</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Random Forests</strong>: Pattern recognition in historical price data</li>
            <li><strong>Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)</strong>: Feature importance ranking for predictive indicators</li>
            <li><strong>Neural Networks (LSTMs)</strong>: Sequential pattern detection in time-series data</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Unsupervised Learning</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>K-Means Clustering</strong>: Market regime identification (bull, bear, range-bound)</li>
            <li><strong>Principal Component Analysis (PCA)</strong>: Dimensionality reduction for multi-asset analysis</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Natural Language Processing (NLP)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Sentiment Analysis</strong>: Transformer models (BERT-based) for social media and news</li>
            <li><strong>Topic Modeling</strong>: LDA (Latent Dirichlet Allocation) for narrative tracking</li>
            <li><strong>Named Entity Recognition</strong>: Identifying mentions of specific tokens and projects</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>6.2 Statistical Models</h2>
        <p>
            In addition to ML, traditional statistical methods provide robust baselines:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>GARCH Models</strong>: Volatility forecasting</li>
            <li><strong>ARIMA/SARIMA</strong>: Time-series trend analysis</li>
            <li><strong>Monte Carlo Simulation</strong>: Probability distribution modeling</li>
            <li><strong>Correlation Analysis</strong>: Cross-asset relationship quantification</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="note">
            <strong>Important:</strong> Model outputs are probabilistic, not deterministic. Aigen AI presents confidence intervals and probability distributions rather than single-point predictions.
        </div>
